@article{Clark1978,
abstract = {This article has examined the existing economic literature as it relates to individual and population aging. The continuation of low rates of fertility and reductions in mortality rates of the elderly has revived the interest of economists in the examination of the economic impacts of aging populations. This review highlights the most important areas of research in the literature on aging. The population of the United States is expected to age significantly throughout the next 25-to-50 years. The economic consequences of the impending age structure changes should command a high priority in both theoretical and policy-oriented research by economists. The economic influences of population aging result from individual differences in behavior over the life cycle combined with the increase in the relative number of older persons. Rigorous examination of life-cycle activity is a relatively recent development in economic analysis. Considerable work remains to be done that will enable researchers to explore the labor supply and expenditure decisions as individuals' age. The continued rise of married women's labor force participation necessitates that the theoretical framework include dual-career families. The inclusion of flexible retirement ages and better measures of health status are required to permit the analysis of policy changes that alter social security and private pensions.},
annote = {I) Population aging: its sources and impact on dependency.

Population aging : increase in the proportion of a population in the older age groups.
Reflected in the increase in a population's median age.

1) Determinants of age structure changes.

Age structure of industrialized countries today : governed primarily by a population's fertility behavior.
Population growth will tend to oscillate probably about zero growth level.

2) Dependency ratios and income transfers.

Under replacement-level fertility, projections of total dependency costs depend on the relative cost of providing benefits to the young and to the old.

Average cost of supporting dependents will be higher in a stationary population than in a growing one.

Expenditure on children is in the form of investment in human capital.
={\textgreater} Reallocation of resources toward older dependents may lower the future rate of economic growth.

Increased proportion of the national income required to support older dependents if the retirement age is allowed to decline.

II) Economic status of the elderly.

1) Income of the aged.

Rising real wages during worklife have also contributed to the increasing income of successive aged cohorts.

2) Income sources and their importance.

Social security : most prevalent source of income for aged individuals.

Composition of the income of the elderly : varies significantly with the level of income.

Share of income represented by social security benefits : declines sharply with the rising income of beneficiaries.
={\textgreater} Due to the progressivity of the benefit structure.

Proportion of income derived from other public pensions, private pensions, earnings and assets : rise steeply with increases in the level of total income.

3) Replacement rates by income sources.

As the earnings record of a worker rises, the social security replacement rate falls rapidly.

Ability of a worker to accumulate assets during worklife is a function of :
- the size of his annual earnings.
- whether his earnings were interrupted by periods of unemployment or disability.

4) Inflation and the income of the aged.

In presence of unanticipated inflation: the largest decline in wealth is for the elderly.

Consumer Price Index : used to determine changes in government benefits.
={\textgreater} May result in the elderly being under/over compensated for inflation if their buyings habits are markedly different than that of youger families.

III) Life-cycle patterns of economic activity.

1) Job performance and work capacity.

Effect of age on productivity : insignificant.

Introduction of new technologies : some portion of the older worker's human capital has become obsolete ={\textgreater} Depreciation.
Higher training costs for older workers, particularly those with lower than average education and skills.

Variation within an age group is usually larger than the producitvity differences between cohorts.

Work injuries do not increase with age : although the types of accidents involving older workers result in longer periods of disability for the older employee.

2) Age-earnings profiles.

Behavior of earnings with age is more readily observable.

After entry into the labor force, annual earnings are low.
Income of each successive age group being higher.
Earnings peak achived by 45-54 years-old.

The higher the level of education and/or skill level of the job, the later the age at which income is maximized.

Increase in income due to two phenomena :
- worker's added experience : greater for young men.
- economic growth : greater for young men.

3) Life-cycle models.

Offer a system that can incorporate the complex interactions of savings and variable retirement age, obsolesence of skills and assets, education and retirement age.

IV) Labor supply of the elderly.

1) Labor supply, retirement and inconsistencies in literature.

Measure of labor market activity: labor force participation rates and receipt of pension benefits.
It is possible for a person to be counted as retired by some of these measures, but not others.

2) Factors influencing the labor supply of elderly.

Main factors : pension systems (benefits and labor force restrictions) and health status.
={\textgreater} + interaction of both of them.

Elderly may move to part time work due to the untaxed portion of income.

Compulsory retirement : justified by increasing health problems, inflexibility to work, pay scales, etc.
Termination of seniority and job-specific skills may imply a fall in the wage offers that older workers receive.

Unemployment : unsuccessful job search induces workers to withdraw from the labor force.
={\textgreater} Labor force varies inversely with changes in unemployment rates.
Over the business cycle, older cohorts as a group may suffer a net loss in employment.

Wage change : ambiguous effect due to negative income effect and positive substitution effect.

Asset income : influence of nonwage income on the labor supply decision is unambiguously negative.

Occupation : desire to remain on the job is probably correlated with prestige and physical stress required by a particular job.

V) Pensions.

1) Social security.

Political forces in a democracy will produce a social insurance budget that is too large as judged by economic efficiency criteria.

Question concerning the solvency of the social security program : 3 sources.
i) Short-run cyclical problems : prolonged recession that reduces tax revenus and increases the number of beneficiaries.
ii) Long-run problem created by the rising structure of replacement rates due to over-indexing.
iii) Demographic pressure of the chaning age structure of the population : will increase the beneficary-worker ratio necessitating a restructuring of the tax and benefit schedule.

Payroll tax to finance social security will be shifted to labor (under nul wage elasticity).
But labor supply response and welfare changes depend not only on the tax but also on the manner in which benefits are paid to workers.

Rate of return on taxes : population aging will result in increased taxes and will lower future returns.

Impact on savings : indetermined.
- Social security wealth reduces individual savings.
- But at the same time may induce workers to retire at an earlier age and thus increasing savings per year in the labor force.

2) Private pensions.

Factors influencing coverage and vesting : length of job tenure was positively correlated with pension coverage as was the level of compensation.
Union status and size of the firm are important determinants of pension coverage.

VI) Macroeconomic response to age structural change.

Behavioral response of an individual aging assumes two interrelated forms : 
a) Reaction to the physical and psychological effects of aging.
b) Change in economic behavior over the life-cycle.

Economic reaction of a nation to population aging is two-fold :
a) response of the autonomous individual to his aging
b) reaction of a population to the collective impact of an increas in the fraction of its old members.

1) Age and productivity.

Age structure will have an impaxct on the nation's economic efficiency and rate of productivity growth.

2) Age and mobility.

Horizontal mobility : inversely related to age.
Vertical mobility : members of a growing population will be promoted more rapidly on average than members of a stationary population.

3) Age an consumption.

Aging may affect the structure of demand.
Increase in the dependency ratio : tends to increase threshold levels of some goods (food, clothing and services) but has the reverse effect on housing and durables.

4) Aging and saving.

Early retirement inceases saving.

Tendency for greater per capita capital formation is due to the cessation of population growth that eliminates the need for added capital to equip net additions to the labor force.

Carrying population aging to the point where it is stationary and stable entails a risk : fertility can be reduced to below replacement, with the result that the income transfers necessary to support the aged become burdensome and unfavorable to capital formation.},
author = {Clark, Robert and Kreps, Juanita and Spengler, Joseph},
doi = {10.2307/2723470},
file = {:C$\backslash$:/Users/FabienP/OneDrive/[PhD] Paper/Literature/Clark, Kreps, Spengler - 1978 - Journal of Economic Literature.pdf:pdf},
isbn = {9780324579611},
issn = {00220515},
journal = {Journal of Economic Literature},
number = {3},
pages = {919--962},
title = {{Economics of aging: A survey}},
volume = {16},
year = {1978}
}
