@article{Acemoglu2002,
abstract = {For many problems in macroeconomics, development economics, labour economics, and international trade, whether technical change is biased towards particular factors is of central importance. This paper develops a simple framework to analyse the forces that shape these biases. There are two major forces affecting equilibrium bias: the price effect and the market size effect. While the former encourages innovations directed at scarce factors, the latter leads to technical change favouring abundant factors. The elasticity of substitution between different factors regulates how powerful these effects are, determining how technical change and factor prices respond to changes in relative supplies. If the elasticity of substitution is sufficiently large, the long run relative demand for a factor can slope up. I apply this framework to develop possible explanations to the following questions: why technical change over the past 60 years was skill biased, and why the skill bias may have accelerated over the past 25 years? Why new technologies introduced during the late eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries were unskill biased? What is the effect of biased technical change on the income gap between rich and poor countries? Does international trade affect the skill bias of technical change? What are the implications of wage push for technical change? Why is technical change generally labour augmenting rather than capital augmenting?},
annote = {Acemoglu develops a framework which generalizes the existing endogenous technical change models to allow for technical change to be directed towards different factors. The firms invest in a technology complementing a particular factor. The targeted factor is determined by two competing effects and the dominance of one or another. These two effects are:
* price effect: creates incentives to develop technologies used in the production of more expensive goods (or factor), i.e. scarce factors;
* market size effect: encourages the development of technologies that have the larger market, i.e. abundant factor.

The relative strengths of those two effects are determined by the elasticity of substitution between the factors. When the latter is low, the price effect dominates. When it is high, the market size effect does. The model contains a market for technology development where a firm has a monopoly. According to the elasticity of substitution between the factors sigma, the net present discounted value of profits for the monopolist to develop one technology producing more factor i are either: increasing in i factor price when sigma{\textless}1 or increasing in i factor supply when sigma{\textgreater}1.

Acemoglu defines that two factors are gross substitutes only if the two goods are gross substitutes.

Acemoglu2002 claims that another important determinant of the direction of technical change is the form of the "innovation possibilities frontier". He uses two forms of the model: lab equipment specification and knowledge-based R{\&}D specification. The former being a special case of the latter when there is no state dependence.

Under lab equipment specification, the direction of technical change is endogenized and determined by the relative factor supply and the elasticity of substitution between factors. Acemogu defines the "weak induced-bias hypothesis" where the technology will be endogenously biased in favor of the more abundant factor, the market size effect dominates even when both factors are gross complements. He also defines the "strong induced-bias hypothesis" where the relationship between relative factor supplies and relative factor rewards can be upward sloping when {\$}\backslashsigma{\$} is sufficiently large, i.e. {\$}\backslashsigma{\textgreater}2{\$}. He notices that outside the balanced growth path, there will only be one type of innovation.

Under knowledge-based R$\backslash${\&}D, there is a potential state dependence. The results are very similar to the lab equipment specification. However, the growth rate is determined by the number of scientists. We still have price and market size effects, but also an effect through the relative cost of future R$\backslash${\&}D. When the state dependence is sufficiently high, this effect will play a destabilizing role. Under extreme state dependence, technical change is acting to equate relative factor shares and induced innovations will push the economy towards constant factor shares.

To summarize, there are two important determinants of the direction of technical change: (1) $\backslash$textbf{\{}degree of substitution between the two factors{\}}, when factors are more substitutable, the market size effect and under endogenous technical change, the more abundant factor ; (2) $\backslash$textbf{\{}degree of state dependence in the innovation possibilities frontier{\}}.

$\backslash$cite{\{}Acemoglu2002a{\}} emphasizes four main issues to its analysis: (1) the model exhibits a ``$\backslash$textit{\{}scale effect{\}}'' meaning that the growth rate of the economy increases with the population; (2) profit-motivated R$\backslash${\&}D which is not necessary the case in reality; (3) the factor supplies are given and there is no accumulation; (4) there is no empirical evidence on the degree of state dependence.

Finally, $\backslash$cite{\{}Acemoglu2002a{\}} discusses the application of its framework to different cases: the endogenous skill-biased technical change observed in the US, the directed technical change and cross-country income differences, the effect of international trade on technical change, the Habakkuk hypothesis, the labor-augmenting technical change in the long run, and, the wage push.

Over the past 60 years, the US relative supply of skills has increased rapidly and in the meantime, the college premium has also increased. Technical change is assumed to favor skilled workers and since new tasks are more complex it generates an increasing demand for skills. The model provides explanations for the skill-replacing technical change of the nineteenth century, the secular skill bias of technology throughout the twentieth, and the recent acceleration in this skill bias.

$\backslash$cite{\{}Acemoglu2002a{\}} extends his model with two countries : North (developed) and South (less developed). The latter using technologies developed by the former. However, these technologies may not be appropriated to the needs of South countries. The skill-biased technologies developed in the North due to the structure of the economy will not fully benefit to South country. Thus, the income gap will be larger than it would have been in absence of directed technical change.

$\backslash$cite{\{}Acemoglu2002a{\}} applies his model to international trade. Using the example of a closed country with relative high-skilled workforce. When this country becomes an open country, since skills are scarcer in the world economy than in this country, trade opening will increase the relative price of skill-intensive goods in the country. In this case, the price effect will dominates inducing more innovations directed at skilled workers. He notices that trade opening necessarily increases the skill premium.

Habakkuk hypothesis is that the rapid technical change in the US economy during the nineteenth century resulted from the relative labor scarcity in the US. Specifying the two factors as labor and land (not capital), $\backslash$cite{\{}Acemoglu2002a{\}} shows that his model allows for such an explanation under a sufficient complementarity between those two factors.

$\backslash$cite{\{}Acemoglu2002a{\}}'s model allows a labor-augmenting long-run technical change. However, conditions are strong. Requiring an extreme amount of state dependence in R$\backslash${\&}D and an elasticity of substitution between labor and capital less than 1.

Finally, $\backslash$cite{\{}Acemoglu2002a{\}} discusses the technological implications of a ``$\backslash$textit{\{}wage push shock{\}}'' that took place in continental Europe starting in the late 1960's. The wage push will first increase the labor share and then gradually reduce it by creating capital-biased technical change. Throughout the process, employment falls.},
